    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="227"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d227">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.52/302½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">8 March, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I should like to take time to
                    think this over maturely. I have now no comment to make except this preliminary
                    one: that there seems to me to be a danger that the attempt to disperse the
                    Japanese in this country might lead to the very thing we wish to prevent. It
                    might produce uneasiness in the States to which the Japanese were induced to
                    migrate and to popular clamors there which legislatures might not withstand.
                    Would we not before-hand have to canvass the matter with State authorities and
                    work out a programme which we could be sure from the outset we could carry out.
                    Otherwise the offense might grow greater, not less, in case of failure.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
